00:01:28.820 --> 00:01:32.720
When you're young, you probably
preferred simple

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:35.470
flavors, simple textures.

00:01:35.470 --> 00:01:38.200
You know, lemonade, rice.

00:01:38.200 --> 00:01:41.920
Simple tastes, simple flavors
when you were young, perhaps.

00:01:41.920 --> 00:01:44.090
Candy, cola.

00:01:44.090 --> 00:01:47.120
And as you've gotten a little
bit older, you've begun to

00:01:47.120 --> 00:01:49.910
crave more complex flavors.

00:01:49.910 --> 00:01:56.060
The seemingly paradoxical
flavors of like a briny caviar

00:01:56.060 --> 00:02:01.480
that's also savory, or a dark
chocolate that's bittersweet,

00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:05.620
or a wine for some of you, like
an earthy Bordeaux wine.

00:02:05.620 --> 00:02:08.699
More complex flavors.

00:02:08.699 --> 00:02:13.970
In the same way that our mouths
crave more complex

00:02:13.970 --> 00:02:20.540
tastes as we age, our minds
crave more complex ideas.

00:02:20.540 --> 00:02:23.950
Young minds crave
simple ideas.

00:02:23.950 --> 00:02:27.200
They crave ideas, but putting
things into buckets and

00:02:27.200 --> 00:02:30.060
understanding where the
pieces fit, what piece

00:02:30.060 --> 00:02:31.730
fits in what bucket.

00:02:31.730 --> 00:02:35.490
And as our minds mature, we
begin to crave more ideas in

00:02:35.490 --> 00:02:39.190
the same way that are mouths
crave more complex tastes.

00:02:39.190 --> 00:02:45.880
And a complex idea that leaders,
especially crave, and

00:02:45.880 --> 00:02:51.085
especially successful leaders
crave, are paradoxical ideas.

00:02:51.085 --> 00:02:54.540
There's a pretty striking piece
of research that looked

00:02:54.540 --> 00:02:58.590
at folks along a broad set of
companies, a broad set of

00:02:58.590 --> 00:03:02.540
industries, a broad set of
countries, and said, what

00:03:02.540 --> 00:03:07.400
separates people who stay in
the middle management level

00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:09.440
from folks to move
up to the top?

00:03:09.440 --> 00:03:11.950
That was the research question
that they asked.

00:03:11.950 --> 00:03:16.580
And there are many answers, but
somewhat surprisingly, the

00:03:16.580 --> 00:03:21.640
thing that stood out was the
preference for paradox.

00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:25.500
That the most successful leaders
have brains that don't

00:03:25.500 --> 00:03:28.740
just deal well with paradoxical
ideas, but crave

00:03:28.740 --> 00:03:31.260
them in the same way that
our palates might

00:03:31.260 --> 00:03:34.860
crave a complex taste.

00:03:34.860 --> 00:03:37.790
I want to share with you today
three paradoxes, and I'll

00:03:37.790 --> 00:03:41.120
present three paradoxes for
your consideration.

00:03:41.120 --> 00:03:42.790
These are the three--

00:03:42.790 --> 00:03:47.720
first, that to have more
excellence, you must have less

00:03:47.720 --> 00:03:49.170
excellence.

00:03:49.170 --> 00:03:51.840
And in particular, to have more
excellence in the things

00:03:51.840 --> 00:03:55.310
that matter most, you must have
less excellence where it

00:03:55.310 --> 00:03:57.050
doesn't matter as much.

00:03:57.050 --> 00:04:01.060
Being purposeful about the way
you think about standards.

00:04:01.060 --> 00:04:04.080
Second, that to have more
collaboration, you must have

00:04:04.080 --> 00:04:05.460
less collaboration.

00:04:05.460 --> 00:04:08.530
And what I mean is, to have more
collaboration where it

00:04:08.530 --> 00:04:11.670
counts, where it leads to the
things that you need more of,

00:04:11.670 --> 00:04:14.660
the kind of innovation that you
need more of, for example,

00:04:14.660 --> 00:04:17.269
the business results that you
need more of, you actually

00:04:17.269 --> 00:04:21.620
need less collaboration in other
areas, in other places.

00:04:21.620 --> 00:04:23.630
And we'll talk about the
problem of too much

00:04:23.630 --> 00:04:24.750
collaboration.

00:04:24.750 --> 00:04:27.980
And we'll talk in particular
about the way that virtue like

00:04:27.980 --> 00:04:33.040
collaboration tends
to act as a mask.

00:04:33.040 --> 00:04:36.300
It prevents us from seeing
what's really going on, which

00:04:36.300 --> 00:04:38.190
we're excusing away
bad behavior.

00:04:38.190 --> 00:04:40.430
We say, hey I'm collaborating,
I'm playing well with others,

00:04:40.430 --> 00:04:42.680
I'm doing what at what
I should be doing.

00:04:42.680 --> 00:04:46.290
When actually, it's masking
some bad behavior.

00:04:46.290 --> 00:04:49.010
In this particular case
of collaboration, not

00:04:49.010 --> 00:04:52.520
collaborating with the kinds
of folks who could be more

00:04:52.520 --> 00:04:54.250
productive for you.

00:04:54.250 --> 00:04:56.620
And the third paradox we'll
look at is that to be more

00:04:56.620 --> 00:04:58.720
creative, you must
be less creative.

00:04:58.720 --> 00:05:03.050
And in particular, we'll talk
about the way that needless

00:05:03.050 --> 00:05:10.040
creativity, narcissistic
creativity, saps energy from

00:05:10.040 --> 00:05:13.890
the pragmatic creativity that
you actually need to get

00:05:13.890 --> 00:05:15.130
things done.

00:05:15.130 --> 00:05:17.780
So there's this interplay
between the good excellence

00:05:17.780 --> 00:05:19.780
and the bad excellence, the good
collaboration and the bad

00:05:19.780 --> 00:05:22.050
collaboration, and the good
creativity and the bad

00:05:22.050 --> 00:05:22.900
creativity.

00:05:22.900 --> 00:05:26.120
That's how we'll spend about
the next 25 minutes, and in

00:05:26.120 --> 00:05:29.320
each of them I'll do a bit of
setup and I'll get you talking

00:05:29.320 --> 00:05:31.560
with somebody next to you to
see if you can uncover some

00:05:31.560 --> 00:05:34.070
times where you've fallen into
the trap of the bad.

00:05:34.070 --> 00:05:37.110
And then I'll have a bit of Q&amp;A
and I'll leave you with

00:05:37.110 --> 00:05:40.550
one last thought, and sign a
few books, and all of this

00:05:40.550 --> 00:05:44.020
will be done by, let's say,
five minutes to two.

00:05:44.020 --> 00:05:44.630
Ready to go?

00:05:44.630 --> 00:05:45.860
AUDIENCE: Uh-huh.

00:05:45.860 --> 00:05:49.420
JAKE BREEDEN: All right, let's
start with excellence.

00:05:49.420 --> 00:05:52.090
So I'm going to give you a
piece of data and then

00:05:52.090 --> 00:05:54.290
together, let's make some
meaning from the data.

00:05:54.290 --> 00:05:58.500
And then let's see if we can
go from the meaning to a

00:05:58.500 --> 00:05:59.800
recommendation.

00:05:59.800 --> 00:06:01.240
So here's the data.

00:06:01.240 --> 00:06:04.730
There's a woman named Emerald
Archer who did her Ph.D. at UC

00:06:04.730 --> 00:06:08.020
Santa Barbara in political
psychology.

00:06:08.020 --> 00:06:13.400
She studied female Marines at
Camp Pendleton, a Marine base

00:06:13.400 --> 00:06:14.970
outside of San Diego.

00:06:14.970 --> 00:06:20.720
And she was interested in one
question, which is, why do

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:25.790
female Marines under perform
their male companions, their

00:06:25.790 --> 00:06:29.720
male colleagues, their male
peers, on the rifle range?

00:06:29.720 --> 00:06:30.080
Right?

00:06:30.080 --> 00:06:33.640
So she studies performance of
Marines on the rifle range

00:06:33.640 --> 00:06:36.490
looking at performance
by gender to try

00:06:36.490 --> 00:06:37.990
to answer this question.

00:06:37.990 --> 00:06:39.600
What is it?

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:44.920
And she did the following
test.

00:06:44.920 --> 00:06:50.250
Her hypothesis was that when the
female Marines were primed

00:06:50.250 --> 00:06:54.540
to think of the test as a test
of gender, they would perform

00:06:54.540 --> 00:06:57.100
worse than if they didn't
think of it as a test of

00:06:57.100 --> 00:06:58.770
gender, that if gender
didn't matter.

00:06:58.770 --> 00:07:02.320
And so what she would do is, she
would, in one condition,

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:04.550
she would prime the female
Marines before they would go

00:07:04.550 --> 00:07:06.580
to the rifle range and
shoot at, by the

00:07:06.580 --> 00:07:08.670
way, 500 meters, right?

00:07:08.670 --> 00:07:11.250
So this is incredibly long
distance when they're shooting

00:07:11.250 --> 00:07:13.020
on the rifle range at
Camp Pendleton.

00:07:13.020 --> 00:07:17.350
And in one condition, she would
prime the women, the

00:07:17.350 --> 00:07:22.460
Marines, to say, there's a lot
of research that says women,

00:07:22.460 --> 00:07:26.370
here's the data, women tend to
under perform, at sort of 85%,

00:07:26.370 --> 00:07:30.330
shoot at about 85% the success
rate of their male colleagues.

00:07:30.330 --> 00:07:31.380
This is a test of that.

00:07:31.380 --> 00:07:32.820
Let's see how we do.

00:07:32.820 --> 00:07:38.240
And then the other group, she
had only women, but she didn't

00:07:38.240 --> 00:07:40.960
tell them that this was a
test of a gender at all.

00:07:40.960 --> 00:07:44.930
She just, it was made to seem
as if it's random, that it

00:07:44.930 --> 00:07:47.915
just happened to be four women
there shooting at a range,

00:07:47.915 --> 00:07:49.410
there are no men around
and there was no

00:07:49.410 --> 00:07:51.760
priming around gender.

00:07:51.760 --> 00:07:55.610
And in fact, when there was no
priming and when there was

00:07:55.610 --> 00:08:00.190
only women there, they shot at
exactly the same level as men.

00:08:00.190 --> 00:08:03.080
Much higher than they had
been shooting before.

00:08:03.080 --> 00:08:08.960
So she presents her research,
and it's quite clear that when

00:08:08.960 --> 00:08:12.850
primed to think of the test
as a test of gender, they

00:08:12.850 --> 00:08:16.080
underperformed the other
scenario, when they weren't

00:08:16.080 --> 00:08:18.260
primed to think of it
as a test of gender.

00:08:18.260 --> 00:08:20.730
So that's the data.

00:08:20.730 --> 00:08:22.660
What do you think is
going on there?

00:08:22.660 --> 00:08:24.690
What's your interpretation
of that?

00:08:24.690 --> 00:08:26.870
AUDIENCE: So when you're
[INAUDIBLE]

00:08:26.870 --> 00:08:29.785
that a certain condition is met,
like you're more likely

00:08:29.785 --> 00:08:33.870
to extreme that position because
maybe you're not

00:08:33.870 --> 00:08:34.360
[INAUDIBLE].

00:08:34.360 --> 00:08:36.640
JAKE BREEDEN: Self-fulfilling
prophecy, essentially.

00:08:36.640 --> 00:08:40.020
So OK, any other ideas?

00:08:40.020 --> 00:08:42.150
Self-fulfilling prophecy, one.

00:08:42.150 --> 00:08:42.770
What else?

00:08:42.770 --> 00:08:46.780
Same data, any other ways
to interpret the data?

00:08:46.780 --> 00:08:47.750
Yep?

00:08:47.750 --> 00:08:49.680
AUDIENCE: You could be worried
that you're getting measured

00:08:49.680 --> 00:08:53.660
on other variables, and so their
focus, like, the idea

00:08:53.660 --> 00:08:56.630
that they're focusing a little
bit less on like, actual

00:08:56.630 --> 00:08:58.990
shoot, like, shooting the rifle
because they're focusing

00:08:58.990 --> 00:09:01.586
on excellence in other
areas, I presume?

00:09:01.586 --> 00:09:02.500
JAKE BREEDEN: Oh,
I see, I see.

00:09:02.500 --> 00:09:04.940
So this would be the
psychological concept there is

00:09:04.940 --> 00:09:05.800
crowding out.

00:09:05.800 --> 00:09:08.040
So they're focused on these
other areas, these other

00:09:08.040 --> 00:09:11.700
variables, that actually don't
help the performance in the

00:09:11.700 --> 00:09:13.770
tested condition, right?

00:09:13.770 --> 00:09:15.680
AUDIENCE: Exactly.

00:09:15.680 --> 00:09:17.620
JAKE BREEDEN: So I'll share with
you Emerald's point of

00:09:17.620 --> 00:09:20.000
view, what she says, and this
is one of these things where

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:21.240
nobody knows what the
real answer is.

00:09:21.240 --> 00:09:22.700
We know what the data is.

00:09:22.700 --> 00:09:25.630
When you go to interpretation,
this is a matter of theory and

00:09:25.630 --> 00:09:26.410
interpretation.

00:09:26.410 --> 00:09:27.810
But I'll tell you hers.

00:09:27.810 --> 00:09:30.160
So Emerald, again,
Emerald Archer

00:09:30.160 --> 00:09:31.790
studying at UC Santa Barbara.

00:09:31.790 --> 00:09:35.210
I interviewed her
about this test.

00:09:35.210 --> 00:09:37.940
It turns out, she grew up
outside of Camp Pendleton as a

00:09:37.940 --> 00:09:38.460
little girl.

00:09:38.460 --> 00:09:42.220
Her father was a contractor
and he worked building the

00:09:42.220 --> 00:09:44.420
barracks on the Marine base.

00:09:44.420 --> 00:09:48.550
And he would often have Marines
over for picnics.

00:09:48.550 --> 00:09:50.980
And so she said, typically on a
Saturday or Sunday we might

00:09:50.980 --> 00:09:53.630
have several Marines grilling
out, having a picnic.

00:09:53.630 --> 00:09:57.780
And she said at a young age, she
says, this is her talking,

00:09:57.780 --> 00:09:59.840
I noticed the following
thing--

00:09:59.840 --> 00:10:04.240
that the women would sort
of take care of

00:10:04.240 --> 00:10:05.460
things at this picnic.

00:10:05.460 --> 00:10:10.240
They would pick up after the
guys, they would get the beers

00:10:10.240 --> 00:10:11.540
or clean up.

00:10:11.540 --> 00:10:16.110
And she said as a young woman,
as a young girl, this seemed

00:10:16.110 --> 00:10:16.750
ridiculous to me.

00:10:16.750 --> 00:10:19.580
And she said, I even noticed
that when the women outranked

00:10:19.580 --> 00:10:24.860
the guys, that gender ended up
being a greater predictor of

00:10:24.860 --> 00:10:28.060
the sort of social subservience
than rank.

00:10:28.060 --> 00:10:31.770
So you would literally have
higher ranking Marines sort of

00:10:31.770 --> 00:10:32.890
taking care of things.

00:10:32.890 --> 00:10:36.320
So she became, at a young age,
you can picture this young

00:10:36.320 --> 00:10:39.440
woman, she's focused on that, so
she dedicates her career to

00:10:39.440 --> 00:10:43.020
trying to understand this, and
it becomes the focus of or a

00:10:43.020 --> 00:10:45.510
Ph.D. dissertation.

00:10:45.510 --> 00:10:49.460
Here's Emerald's, Emerald's
thought is that it's

00:10:49.460 --> 00:10:52.800
essentially along the lines of
the crowding out, that the

00:10:52.800 --> 00:10:55.710
cognitive load, the
cognitive load of

00:10:55.710 --> 00:10:57.470
worrying about this category.

00:10:57.470 --> 00:10:59.890
In this case, women, the
cognitive load of worrying

00:10:59.890 --> 00:11:06.930
about this category, robs the
Marines of the cognitive

00:11:06.930 --> 00:11:10.490
attention they need to give
to this act of shooting.

00:11:10.490 --> 00:11:13.350
And this falls more broadly
under an area called

00:11:13.350 --> 00:11:17.260
stereotype threat, and it's been
shown, for example, with

00:11:17.260 --> 00:11:18.450
student athletes.

00:11:18.450 --> 00:11:23.070
You go to universities and you
get a set of student athletes

00:11:23.070 --> 00:11:25.640
and you prime them to think
of themselves primarily as

00:11:25.640 --> 00:11:28.930
student athletes and says it's
shown that student athletes

00:11:28.930 --> 00:11:31.090
tend to under perform their
colleagues who aren't student

00:11:31.090 --> 00:11:32.630
athletes on standardized
tests.

00:11:32.630 --> 00:11:34.520
Now take a standardized test.

00:11:34.520 --> 00:11:39.340
And sure enough, the sort of the
notion of, I want to prove

00:11:39.340 --> 00:11:40.870
it, ends up being paramount.

00:11:40.870 --> 00:11:44.070
And by the way, the anecdotes
supported the notion when she

00:11:44.070 --> 00:11:46.890
would interview the female
Marines who were engaged in

00:11:46.890 --> 00:11:49.070
these tests in which they'd been
primed, they would say

00:11:49.070 --> 00:11:52.430
things like, I was going
to make sure.

00:11:52.430 --> 00:11:55.680
I was going to make sure that
this false stereotype, that we

00:11:55.680 --> 00:12:00.020
can't shoot as well as
a man, was disproven.

00:12:00.020 --> 00:12:03.570
And this was one woman in the
study, she went on to say, but

00:12:03.570 --> 00:12:05.300
unfortunately, I did
the opposite.

00:12:05.300 --> 00:12:07.020
Unfortunately, I did
the opposite.

00:12:07.020 --> 00:12:11.210
And unfortunately, I did the
opposite, is kind of the theme

00:12:11.210 --> 00:12:13.320
to the study, to the book.

00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:15.140
Unfortunately, I did
the opposite.

00:12:15.140 --> 00:12:17.460
It's the undead unintended
consequence.

00:12:17.460 --> 00:12:23.120
So we're still in excellence,
this first paradox, and the

00:12:23.120 --> 00:12:29.980
punch line is, to get to an
excellent destination,

00:12:29.980 --> 00:12:33.700
sometimes you have to take a
meandering path and lower the

00:12:33.700 --> 00:12:36.410
stakes, lower the standards.

00:12:36.410 --> 00:12:39.920
So think about this now, think
about yourself, think about

00:12:39.920 --> 00:12:40.940
perfectionism.

00:12:40.940 --> 00:12:42.880
Think about times when
you're working

00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:46.120
hard to prove something.

00:12:46.120 --> 00:12:48.090
This is when it's especially
dangerous, when you need to

00:12:48.090 --> 00:12:51.870
prove a point to yourself
or to someone else.

00:12:51.870 --> 00:12:54.480
Maybe it's part of a class
that you belong that's is

00:12:54.480 --> 00:12:56.670
perceived to not to
be as strong.

00:12:56.670 --> 00:12:59.650
It's shown, we have this insight
that the cognitive

00:12:59.650 --> 00:13:02.990
load, it simply becomes
overbearing, your need to

00:13:02.990 --> 00:13:06.160
prove that you can do
this thing well.

00:13:06.160 --> 00:13:10.270
And unfortunately, the opposite,
but you end up

00:13:10.270 --> 00:13:14.010
proving the opposite true,
unfortunately.

