00:40:31.570 --> 00:40:31.740
JAKE BREEDEN: Yeah.

00:40:31.740 --> 00:40:35.470
So I'm a big fan of disruption
as a process.

00:40:35.470 --> 00:40:37.860
And so if you read Clay
Christensen, who wrote "The

00:40:37.860 --> 00:40:40.260
Innovator's Dilemma" and talked
about the innovator's

00:40:40.260 --> 00:40:43.490
dilemma and disruptive
innovation, one of the things

00:40:43.490 --> 00:40:49.590
he talks about is, that being
disruptive is a process.

00:40:49.590 --> 00:40:52.760
And you can't guarantee that you
will disrupt an industry,

00:40:52.760 --> 00:40:55.060
but you can increase the chances
that you will disrupt

00:40:55.060 --> 00:40:57.810
an industry by following
a few steps.

00:40:57.810 --> 00:41:01.690
And so I'm a big believer
in what he did '97 with

00:41:01.690 --> 00:41:03.800
"Innovator's Dilemma" and in
2003 with "Innovator's

00:41:03.800 --> 00:41:07.180
Solution." In "Innovator's
Solution" in particular, he

00:41:07.180 --> 00:41:10.340
talks about, what is the job
to be done by the customer?

00:41:10.340 --> 00:41:12.690
And how am I going to really
understand the job that's

00:41:12.690 --> 00:41:13.600
